he official religion of the realm, bishops and priests everywhere struggled  to "Christianize" the urban spaces still dominated by Greco-Roman monuments and festivals. During this period of upheaval, when congregants seemingly attended everything but their own "orthodox" church, many ecclesiastical leaders began simultaneously to promote aggressive and insidious depictions of the demonic. In City of Demons, Dayna S. Kalleres investigates this developing discourse and the church-sponsored rituals that went along with it, showing how shifting ecclesiastical demonologies and evolving practices of exorcism profoundly shaped Christian life in the fourth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aDemonologyxChristianity. 0aDemonologyxHistory of doctrinesyEarly church, ca. 30-600. 0aDemonologyxHistoryyTo 1500. 7aRELIGION / Antiquities & Archaeology.2bisacsh  a4th century.  achristian history.  achristian power.  achristianity.  acity life.  acivic.  ademonologist.  aecclesiastical authority.  aecclesiastical demonologies.  aecclesiastical leaders.  aemperor constantine.  aengaging.  aexorcism.  aexorcist.  agovernment and governing.  agreco roman festivals.  agreco roman monuments.  ahistorical.  ahistory of christianity.  alate antiquity.  alate roman era.  alively.  apage turner.  apolitical.  aroman empire.  arome.  aurban bishoprics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052027647540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095684140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520956841423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520956841/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA